01:50.840 --> 01:55.680
internet so that we can take advantage of the opportunities that the web and the internet

01:55.680 --> 02:01.880
offers us to be able to keep our clients and customers happy, but we may also have what

02:01.960 --> 02:10.480
are called a DMZ which is a sub network where we're going to put services that may be required

02:10.480 --> 02:16.720
from the outside internet, that means people that are trying to order our products and

02:16.720 --> 02:22.360
interface with us in a nice easy way requires us to have applications that we're going to

02:22.360 --> 02:29.000
put in the DMZ as opposed to letting them come in to the internal network and so that's

02:29.000 --> 02:34.800
where we're going to put things related to any service that is required from the outside

02:34.800 --> 02:40.920
internet, but if you think about wireless this is also where we want to put our Wi-Fi capabilities

02:40.920 --> 02:47.080
because then anybody connecting to those Wi-Fi access points, if they want to be able

02:47.080 --> 02:52.920
to get into the internal network we'll still have to go through the firewall which is there

02:53.000 --> 02:59.880
to provide security so that we only allow what should be allowed in the internal network so

02:59.880 --> 03:06.600
that ultimately we are protecting the value of those assets and services that are ultimately

03:06.600 --> 03:13.160
inside of our network, so if you look at the architecture that is depicted here that is a

03:13.160 --> 03:18.440
